# HIPAA Compliance (SummerySky)

Protect PHI end-to-end: minimize collection, encrypt at rest, redact before any external AI, and keep logs PHI-free.

## Required Practices
- Treat all direct identifiers and clinical data as PHI; follow the HHS Safe Harbor list for redaction coverage.
- Store PHI only in encrypted local storage (IndexedDB + WebCrypto); never in plaintext `chrome.storage.*` or logs.
- Redact PHI before any AI interaction; only send de-identified payloads to external providers.
- When capturing UI HTML for AI guidance, strip text content and input values and remove URL query/path data; only share sanitized, redacted snapshots.
- Keep redaction maps encrypted and local-only; rehydration is performed locally just before export.
- Do not include PHI in issue reports, debug bundles, or telemetry; enforce redaction and PHI scanning checks.
- Use least-privilege scopes and explicit user consent for any external API access.
- Provide a user-visible "data purge" control to clear local PHI and redaction maps.

## PHI Redaction Standards
- Redact names, DOB, MRN, phone, email, address, portal identifiers, and any free-text that can identify a patient.
- Use deterministic placeholders (e.g., `[[PATIENT_NAME_1]]`) scoped to a patient key.
- Verify redaction coverage with automated tests and runtime checks before AI prompt generation.

## Compliance Guardrails
- No PHI in console logs or error messages; use hashed/internal ids.
- Audit trail entries must be non-PHI and include correlation ids for traceability.
- Retention policies must include TTL and size limits for logs, bundles, and transient caches.

## Verification
- Add PHI-leak tests for logs, prompts, issue bundles, and exported artifacts.
- Document any exception explicitly in an ADR and get approval before shipping.
